## Section 1 ##

### Extracting the full dataset for all four books together ###
books <- gutenberg_download(c(219,844,43,4300), mirror ="http://mirrors.xmission.com/gutenberg/")

### Now creating a tidy text and removing stop words and sorting the top words ###
books <- books %>%
  unnest_tokens(word,text) %>%
  anti_join(get_stopwords(source = "smart"))
Joining, by = "word"
books_count <- books %>%
  count(word , sort = TRUE)

books_count <- head(books_count , 20)

### Ploting the top 20 words ###
 
books_count %>% 
  filter(n > 70) %>% 
  mutate(word = reorder(word, n)) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(word, n)) + 
    geom_col() +
    coord_flip() +
    labs(x = "Word \n", y = "\n Count ", title = "Top 20 Frequent Words \n") +
    geom_text(aes(label = n), hjust = 1.2, colour = "white", fontface = "bold") +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5), 
        axis.title.x = element_text(face="bold", colour="darkblue", size = 12),
        axis.title.y = element_text(face="bold", colour="darkblue", size = 12))

###  Creating word frequency plots for each of the three authors using James Joyce as the standard ###

Frequency_Propostion <- bind_rows(mutate(Conrad_all_book, author = "Joseph Conrad"),
                       mutate(Wilde_all_books, author = "Oscar Wilde"),
                       mutate(Stevenson_all_book, author = "Robert Louis"),
                       mutate(Joyce_all_book, author = "James Joyce")) %>% 
  mutate(word = str_extract(word, "[a-z']+")) %>%
  count(author, word) %>%
  group_by(author) %>%
  mutate(proportion = n / sum(n)) %>%     
  select(-n) %>%                          
  spread(author, proportion) %>%          
  gather(author, proportion, `Joseph Conrad`:`Oscar Wilde`:`Robert Louis`)

### Calculating the tf_idf for all the tokens in the combined dataset. Using the bind_tf-idf function ###

book_words <- books %>%
  count(gutenberg_id , word, sort = TRUE)
    

tf_idf_of_books <- book_words %>%
  bind_tf_idf(word, gutenberg_id, n)
